Inline Code Example
=================

This document demonstrates the new inline code formatting with backticks.

Basic Usage
----------

=> Use single backticks like `this` to create inline code
=> The code will be styled with a special background and color
=> Perfect for referencing variable names, commands, or short code snippets

Examples
~~~~~~~

Here are some examples of inline code formatting:

1. Variable names: `user_name`, `count`, `is_active`
2. Function calls: `print("Hello World")`, `calculate_total(items)`
3. HTML tags: `<div>`, `<span>`, `<a href="#">`
4. File paths: `/usr/local/bin`, `C:\Program Files\`
5. Commands: `npm install`, `git commit -m "message"`

Inline Code in Lists
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

=> The `map()` function transforms each element in an array
=> Use `filter()` to remove unwanted elements
=> The `reduce()` function combines all elements into a single value

Inline Code with Styling
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

You can combine inline code with other Ddown features:

=> Inline code in a heading: `code` in headings
=> Inline code with links: [`linked code`](https://example.com)
=> Inline code with inline styles: `styled code` {@ font-weight: bold; }

Code Blocks vs Inline Code
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

For longer code snippets, use code blocks with triple backticks:

```python
def greet(name):
    return f"Hello, {name}!"

print(greet("Ddown User"))
```

But for short snippets within text, use `inline code` with single backticks.
